In[]:
def convert_category_fulltimeemployees(employees: int):
    stages = [
        (0, 10_000, "Tiny"),
        (10_001, 100_000, "Small"),
        (100_001, 250_000, "Medium"),
        (250_001, 500_000, "Large"),
        (500_001, 1_000_000, "Massive"),
        (1_000_001, float("inf"), "Giant"),
    ]
    
    for start, end, name in stages:
        if start <= employees <= end:
            return name
    return "Out of range"

def convert_category_currentprice(price: float):
    stages = [
        (8.56, 50, "Penny Stock"),       
        (50.01, 500, "Affordable"),    
        (500.01, 2000, "Mid-Cap"),     
        (2000.01, 5000, "Blue Chip"),   
        (5000.01, 9000, "Premium"),     
    ]
    
    for start, end, name in stages:
        if start <= price <= end:
            return name
    return "Out of range"
In[]:
data['Fulltimeemployees_TEXT'] = data['Fulltimeemployees'].apply(lambda x: convert_category_fulltimeemployees(float(x)))
data['Currentprice_TEXT'] = data['Currentprice'].apply(lambda x: convert_category_currentprice(float(x)))

Hypothesis Check

Hypothesis:

Does Market Cap and EDITDA depends on the amount of Full-time employees

Firstly, let's check the relation between market cap and employees

In[]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.scatter(data['Fulltimeemployees'], data['Marketcap'])
plt.xlabel('Full-Time Employees')
plt.ylabel('Market Cap')
plt.title('Market Cap vs. Full-Time Employees')
plt.show()

As you probably noticed, the fewer amount of employees the lower is market cap, but there are some blowouts in each direction.

Now, let's do the same check for EDITDA

In[]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.scatter(data['Fulltimeemployees'], data['Ebitda'])
plt.xlabel('Full-Time Employees')
plt.ylabel('EBITDA')
plt.title('EBITDA vs. Full-Time Employees')
plt.show()

Almost the same looking chart, but now more points are not just "stuck" in the bottom position. Let's zoom in for better experience.

In[]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.scatter(data[data["Fulltimeemployees"] < 100_000]['Fulltimeemployees'], data[data["Fulltimeemployees"] < 100_000]['Ebitda'])
plt.xlabel('Full-Time Employees')
plt.ylabel('EBITDA')
plt.title('EBITDA vs. Full-Time Employees')
plt.show()

Based on that, we can definetely tell that most of the companies have around 20k full-time employees and they have almost the same EBITDA

Now, let's go on to the more complicated chart.

So, now it consists of:

+ Market Cap
+ Full-time Employees
+ EBITDA
In[]:
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
scatter = plt.scatter(
    data['Fulltimeemployees'], 
    data['Marketcap'], 
    c=data['Ebitda'], 
    s=data['Ebitda'] / 1e9,
    alpha=0.7, 
    edgecolor='face'
)

plt.colorbar(scatter, label='EBITDA')
plt.title('Marketcap vs Fulltimeemployees by EBITDA', fontsize=16)

In[]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize=(20, 15))
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')

After complicated research, I came to the conclusion that Company's Ebitda and Market Cap expectedly depends on the company size (Amount of workers)
